Crossposted-To: comp.infosystems.www,comp.windows.x,comp.windows.x.i386unix,comp.windows.x.motif,gnu.misc.discuss,comp.sources.d
From: rhealey@sirius.aggregate.com (Rob Healey)
Subject: Re: Tough! Quit griping! Was: Re: Don't use Motif for free sw: it now requires runtime royalties!
Date: Tue, 30 Nov 1993 19:05:52 GMT

In article <HOPS.93Nov30094504@herts.x.co.uk>,
Mike Hopkirk <hops@x.co.uk> wrote:
>pcg> 1) There are complicated licensing issues that can cause problems to you
>pcg>    or to us, and that reduce the potential for usefulness and widespread
>pcg>    adoption of any free sw that depends on OSF/Motif.
>No - read the clarification...
>If its still unclear mail OSF with your exact situation and what you want to
>do...
>
        Actually, using a Free toolkit would simplify things the most. Why
        would I want to spend MONEY on a project that is freely redistributable?

        Why would I want to have to worry about if end users have a runtime
        license or not?

        Why would I want to be FORCED to link statically, and thus create
        even a BIGGER monster, in order to dodge this restriction or that?

        Using a Free toolkit would solve all the problems; no questions to
        get answered at all. If someone can ftp the freely redistributable
        code they should be able to ftp the freely distributable toolkit.

        If there is a Free version of something available why bother with
        a commercial version? Support? Support for most commercial applications
        is a VERY unfunny joke. Every forum I've seen, USENET, compu$erve,
        Delphi, Prodigy ALL offer better support than most commercial vendors
        and now commercial vendors even have the gall to CHARGE for lousy
        technical or end user support!!! At least with for-charge car,
        electronics or services warrantees I feel like I'm actually getting
        something for my money...

        At least with freely redistributable code you can either 1) Fix it
        yourself, or 2) have a decent chance of actually getting it fixed
        in less than a commercial 6 month time frame.

                -Rob

#include <std/disclaimers.h>
Speaking for myself only of course.

