In article <kaleb.754677773@kanga.x.org>, kaleb@expo.lcs.mit.edu (Kaleb Keithley) writes:
|> Why is this cross-posted to so many groups?
|> 
|> deal@ait.nrl.navy.mil (Butch Deal) writes:
|> >In article Frank.Peters@MsState.Edu (Frank Peters) writes:
|> >|> In article <CH9Jnu.M54@uceng.uc.edu>
|> >|>  gjunker@ddt.eng.uc.edu (Gregory Junker) says:
|> >|> 
|> >|> >        - Slow
|> >|> 
|> >|> I doubt it.  You may have a slow X server or slow hardware or a slow
|> >|> Motif application (or a slow Motif window manager, which is just another
|> >|> application).  I've seen and heard nothing to suggest that the Motif
|> >|> toolkit inherently makes your applications slow.
|> >I agree.  It is slow in the sence that it wastes alot of cpu time.  Just
|> >because you have a fast computer, you do not want to waste all the cpu time
|> >with a GUI.  Motif is overly bloated
|> 
|> Perhaps someone would like to substantiate heresay with some factual data. 
|> At my prior employer I used Motif to develop a "real-time" status display 
|> to monitor ground equipment. The programs responded instantaneously and
|> repeated profile analysis showed that the negligible amount of CPU that 
|> they did use was not in Motif. I would characterize Motif as anything but 
|> slow.

a comparison of two programs like xnet vers. 1.3 and mosaic.  Actually doing a
trace with xnet and just moving the pointer around in the mosaic window. 
ps -auCS on a sun690 MP (super sparc) with X11r5 (patch 26) and piewm with 
raisedelay patch installed.

USER       PID %CPU %MEM   SZ  RSS TT STAT START  TIME COMMAND
deal      7890  0.0  3.8 3600 4668 co S    Nov 29 14:41 /usr/bin/X11/Xsun :0 -au
deal     16121  0.0  0.4   80  540 p2 S    14:09   0:00 /usr/local/bin/xnet
deal     16123  0.0  0.0 1308    0 p2 IW   14:09   0:02 Mosaic

xnet trace to sun.com (9 hops away from here)
just moveing the pointer in the mosaic window.

USER       PID %CPU %MEM   SZ  RSS TT STAT START  TIME COMMAND
deal      7890  0.8  3.8 3600 4668 co S    Nov 29 14:45 /usr/bin/X11/Xsun :0 -au
deal     16121  0.0  0.4   80  544 p2 S    14:09   0:00 /usr/local/bin/xnet
deal     16123  0.0  0.7 1308  792 p2 S    14:09   0:03 Mosaic

bring up help and info windows of xnet and another trace to sun.com
move pointer around some more in mosaic window.

USER       PID %CPU %MEM   SZ  RSS TT STAT START  TIME COMMAND
deal      7890  0.0  3.8 3600 4668 co S    Nov 29 14:50 /usr/bin/X11/Xsun :0 -au
deal     16121  0.0  0.4   84  544 p2 S    14:09   0:00 /usr/local/bin/xnet
deal     16123  0.0  0.8 1308  936 p2 S    14:09   0:04 Mosaic

three traces with xnet and a source route trace, help 5 times
get a local home page for mosaic

USER       PID %CPU %MEM   SZ  RSS TT STAT START  TIME COMMAND
deal      7890  0.0  3.8 3600 4668 co S    Nov 29 15:01 /usr/bin/X11/Xsun :0 -au
deal     16121  0.0  0.5   88  552 p2 S    14:09   0:00 /usr/local/bin/xnet
deal     16123  0.0  0.8 1416  948 p2 S    14:09   0:05 Mosaic

This is also with a local console.  The network load becomes very apparent
with motif if you are useing a remote computer and have a heavy  ether load,
or a PPP link.

|> 
|> >|> >        - Difficult (read impossible) to program
|> >|> 
|> >|> I can't really argue this since I've never tried to write a Motif program.
|> >|> But the various applications out there seem to argue against this.
|> 
|> You obviously haven't tried to program in the raw Xlib, Macintosh,
|> Presentation Manager, or Windows environments.

I didn't write that motif was difficult to write in, but I have writen Xlib, 
XT, Mac, Motif, OpenLook, Xview, and suntools programs.  Motif is not
particularly harder than any of the rest although I think the docs are a bit
harsh.  I do much prefer Xlib though over the others, although Xview is very
easy to come up with a quick easy application that looks nice.

|> 
|> >Many of them were writen with a GUI tool.  These GUI tools, although very easy
|> >to use, yeald very hefty programs.  I have seen a 35Meg motif binary (striped).
|> >This is not always the case in any means.
|> 
|> I sincerely doubt this had anything to do with Motif. The whole library
|> is ~500k on a Sun SPARC. Even if your link editor pulls in every last
|> module in libXm, libXt, and libX11, (statically linked) the libraries
|> only contribute ~1.5meg, unstripped. That 35 meg came from somewhere
|> else.
|> 
I will not debate this point much as I did not look at the source code for
this program.  I think almost everyone has seen how much larger a motif
program is than an Xlib or Xt program that does the same.

|> --
|> 
|> Kaleb Keithley
|> 

