In article <hastyCH9q0u.4vo@netcom.com>,
Amancio Hasty Jr <hasty@netcom.com> wrote:
>                       NetBSD   -- Public release by another group which 
>                                   has a slight different goal. For intance,
>                                   there is a NetBSD amiga port group. This
>                                   group tends to be more technically
>                                   aggressive. It too will have a CDROM.
>                                   Currently, NetBSD has dynamic shared 
>                                   libraries similar to the sun os mechanism.
>
>
        NetBSD is aimed at more architectures than just Intel. Currently
        it supports SPARC, Intel and Motorola m68k with Sun3, sun4, Intel,
        Amiga, Mac and other machines. It appears it's end goal is to
        provide a universal UNIX-like OS across as many platforms as possible.

        The other BSD's and Linux appear to be concerned primarily with Intel
        although there is an m68k Linux port(s) under way.

                -Rob

